      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. i'll try pressing it in harder next time. it's just weird because when i look at the corners or peek into the gaps where the mud didn't fully fill in, it feels like there's just a lot of hollow space or weird empty pockets behind the panels. is it normal for the wall to feel like it's got a lot of little voids or empty cavities behind the surface like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is not normal for the finished drywall surface to feel like it has large, hollow voids behind the mud; this suggests a potential issue with the underlying installation or the tape adhesion. If you feel significant empty pockets, it might mean the joint compound didn't properly bond to the seams or the mud hasn't fully filled the cavity. You may need to lightly sand the area to help the next coat key into any remaining voids, or carefully embed a small amount of fresh mud into those specific spots.",
      "source": "target",
